ported nearly 80 per cent Of

BOSTON Over fifty percent
of the Negroes in the United
States who earned electorate de-
grees in religious fields during
the past decade received them
at Boston University, reported
DR.. Shelby Rocks of the Fund
for Theological Education at
Princeton, New Jersey.


Fourteen out of the rwenty-six
doctorates awarded to Negroes
in this country from lo53-lo63
were given by the Universitys
School Of Theology In conjunc-
tion with the graduate school and
some Of the graduates have al
ready risen to prominent places
in American society.


The remining degrees were
awarded by the following col
leges and universities: Divinity
School at the University Of Chi
cago, one degree: Hartford Theo-
logical Seminary, one: Harvard
Divinity School, two: Southern
California, one; the Theological
School at Drew University, two:
Union College in New York, one;
Union College in Virginia. one:
Vanderbilt Divinity School. one;
Yale Divinity School, two.


DR.. Martin Luther King, Jr..
President of the Southern Chris
tian Leadership Conference at
Atlanta, Ca, best known Of the
group, received a Ph.D. from
Boston University in 1855 upon
completion Of his thesis entitled:
ga Comparison of the Concep-
tions Of God In the Thinking Of
Paul Tillich and Henry Nelson
Wieman."


Of eight doctorates that were
earned nationally in the field Of
social ethics, sevenwere attained
at Boston University. Included
among those who received doc
torates in this field are: Charles
Eric Lincoln, Ph.D. 1860. pro-
fessor at Clark College in Geor-
gia, who published his thesis
entitled, "The Black Muslims
in the United States:" Evans
Edgar Crawford Jr., Ph.D. 1857.
the Dean of the Rankin Chapel
at Howard University in Wash
ington, Dc, whose thesis topic
